description:
Lines 504-507 in secretx-tpm2/src/lib.rs:

```rust
let r_offset = 32usize.saturating_sub(r.len());
let s_offset = 32usize.saturating_sub(s.len());
out[r_offset..32].copy_from_slice(&r[r.len().saturating_sub(32)..]);
out[32 + s_offset..64].copy_from_slice(&s[s.len().saturating_sub(32)..]);
```

The first `saturating_sub` on each pair (e.g. `32usize.saturating_sub(r.len())`) handles right-aligning a short component. The second `saturating_sub` (e.g. `r[r.len().saturating_sub(32)..]`) silently truncates from the left if the component exceeds 32 bytes. For P-256, r and s are mathematically bounded to [1, n-1] where n < 2^256, so they can never exceed 32 bytes — the second `saturating_sub` is dead code.

What goes wrong if this stays: A future reader cannot tell whether the >32 case is a real possibility being handled or dead defensive code. If a TPM bug or API change ever produced oversized components, the truncation would silently produce an invalid signature instead of returning an error.

Suggested fix: Replace the defensive truncation with a debug_assert or explicit error:

```rust
// P-256 components are at most 32 bytes (order < 2^256).
if r.len() > 32 || s.len() > 32 {
    return Err(SecretError::Backend {
        backend: BACKEND,
        source: format!("ECDSA-P256 component too large: r={}, s={}", r.len(), s.len()).into(),
    });
}
let mut out = vec![0u8; 64];
out[32 - r.len()..32].copy_from_slice(r);
out[64 - s.len()..64].copy_from_slice(s);
```

This makes the invariant explicit and turns a silent corruption into a loud error.
